+{"type":"message","id":"17efe9c3","parentId":"d9e7836c","timestamp":"2026-03-29T22:19:20.777Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Parent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: openai-codex/gpt-5.4-mini\nSource items: 73\n\nOverview:\nThe discussion centered on whether LightRAG-style simplification would fit this repo’s AI stack, then shifted into a broader AI pipeline optimization effort. The repo already has a fairly advanced RAG/AI architecture: Spring Boot backend, Pinecone vector search, prompt templates, eval harnesses, and derived read models. The resulting direction was to keep a reusable experiment framework, on-demand A/B evaluation, and a few quality/cost improvements, all with backward-compatible defaults.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Proceed with a reusable live experiment framework, not just one-off eval scripts.\n- Keep experiments default-off so current behavior is unchanged unless explicitly enabled.\n- Use OpenRouter as the sole LLM gateway; do not add direct provider calls.\n- Use existing eval datasets/judging infrastructure for on-demand A/B comparisons.\n- Record experiment/model metadata in existing audit-related fields rather than adding schema migrations.\n- Add prompt caching support for Anthropic models via OpenRouter.\n- Add SQL routing for analytical questions to use read models instead of vector search.\n- Keep HyDE as an opt-in, experiment-controlled RAG enhancement.\n- Add chunk-size monitoring/analysis as a diagnostic/observability improvement.\n- A plan file was written: `duet-plan-ai-optimization.md` for duet-based implementation.\n\nConstraints / must-remember items:\n- Implementation should stay backend-only for this plan; no frontend/package/e2e changes.\n- Java 21 / Spring Boot 3.4 stack; avoid introducing new framework dependencies.\n- All new behaviors must be backward compatible and disabled by default.\n- OpenRouter remains the only model gateway.\n- Existing eval tests must continue to pass.\n- The plan assumes no database schema changes.\n- The repo already contains derived read models relevant to SQL routing: UserWeekFact, TeamWeekRollup, RcdoWeekRollup, CarryForwardFact, ComplianceFact.\n- Duet config in `.pi/duet/config.json` shows static checks: `npm run check:static`; unit checks: `npm test`.\n- There is already an in-progress duet run with modified files under `.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-29T18-32-40-613Z-32faa966/` and tracked changes in `AiController` plus new plan recommendation files.\n\nOpen questions:\n- Should the initial implementation keep the full live traffic experiment service, or trim it down later if it proves too heavy?\n- Which exact models should be treated as control/treatment defaults for LLM and embeddings in the reusable A/B harness?\n- Should analytical SQL routing be limited to clearly aggregate/comparison queries, or should it also handle broader reporting-style questions?\n- How much observability is wanted for prompt caching and chunk-size analysis beyond basic logging/counters?\n- Should the A/B runner compare only LLMs initially, or also embeddings and HyDE in the same reusable harness?\n\nUse this handoff as background context. If it conflicts with the explicit task below or the current repository state, prioritize the explicit task and repo state.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Add seven optimization capabilities to the AI pipeline — prompt caching, A/B testing infrastructure, embedding model override (offline eval only), LLM model A/B, HyDE, SQL query routing, and chunk size analysis — all backward-compatible and default-off. The embedding-model A/B experiment is scoped to offline evaluation only (via AbComparisonRunner) because the Pinecone index is fixed at 1536 dimensions matching text-embedding-3-small; routing live queries through text-embedding-3-large (3072-d) would cause dimension mismatches. Backend-only; no frontend, e2e, or schema changes.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 7,\n  \"step